In this tutorial I'm going to introduce what a powerful visualization library Seaborn is, by creating various plots with the Titanic Dataset.

In [1]:
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline
In [2]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [2]:
tips = sns.load_dataset('tips')
In [4]:
tips.head()

Distribution plots¶

In [67]:
sns.distplot(tips['total_bill'])
Out[67]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2d327c49208>

This line is called as a KDE = kernel density estimation

we can remove it as an additional argument in the function¶

In [68]:
sns.distplot(tips['total_bill'], kde = False, bins = 30)
Out[68]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2d32b0e75f8>

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2d326df72e8>

The difference between a histogram and this rugplot is that histogram has bins and count of many dashes are in that bin and shows it as a number. The KDE is built on the rugplot.

In [30]:

Violin plot plays a similar role as boxplot.

In [38]:
sns.violinplot(x = 'day', y = 'total_bill', data = tips)
Out[38]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2d329896208>

The violinplot lets us plot all the elements contained in the dataset, unlike boxplot, it is showing the kernel density of the underlying distribution

In [39]:
sns.violinplot(x = 'day', y = 'total_bill', data = tips, hue = 'sex')
Out[39]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2d3298fd7b8>

If we want to plot a heatmap, our data has to be in a matrix form, meaning the rows and colums are variables

In [73]:

1 1949 February 118

We can tranform this data in a matrix-like form with pivot table

In [84]:
## Cluster map
In [86]:
sns.clustermap(fp, lw = 2)
Out[86]:
<seaborn.matrix.ClusterGrid at 0x2d32b288ef0>

The data is clustered in hierarchy. The years and month are not in proper order

In [91]:
# We can add different arguments to this clustermap
sns.clustermap(fp, lw = 1, cmap = 'Blues', standard_scale= 1)
Out[91]:
<seaborn.matrix.ClusterGrid at 0x2d32e44de10>
